    <td><img src="fest pics" alt="" width="261" /></td>
    <td><p class="style34"><strong>Vaisakhi</strong>&nbsp;(LAST&nbsp;<em>visākhī</em>),  also known as&nbsp;<strong>Baisakhi</strong>,&nbsp;<strong>Vaishakhi</strong>, or&nbsp;<strong>Vasakhi</strong>&nbsp;is  a historical and religious festival in&nbsp;Sikhism&nbsp;and&nbsp;Hinduism. It is  usually celebrated on April 13 or 14 every year.[4][5]<br />
      Vaisakhi marks birth of the Khalsa way of living in the Sikh  religion.[2][1]and  commemorates the formation of&nbsp;Khalsa panth of warriors under Guru Gobind Singh&nbsp;in 1699.[6][7]&nbsp;It  is additionally a spring harvest festival for the Sikhs.[6]Vaisakhi  is also an ancient festival of Hindus, marking the Solar New Year and also  celebrating the spring harvest.[7]&nbsp;It  marks the sacredness of rivers in Hindu culture, it is regionally known by many  names, but celebrated in broadly similar ways.[8][9]&nbsp;Indian subcontinent<br />
      Vaisakhi observes major events in the history of Sikhism and  the&nbsp;Indian subcontient&nbsp;that happened in  the&nbsp;Punjab region[10][11]he  significance of Vaisakhi as a major Sikh festival marking the birth of Sikh  order started after the persecution and execution of&nbsp;Guru Tegh Bahadur&nbsp;for refusing to convert to Islam under the orders of the  Mughal Emperor&nbsp;Aurangzeb. This triggered the coronation of the  tenth Guru of Sikhism and the historic formation of&nbsp;Khalsa, both on the Vaisakhi day.[12][13][14]&nbsp;Vaisakhi  was also the day when colonial British empire officials committed the&nbsp;Jallianwala Bagh massacre&nbsp;on a gathering, an event influential to the Indian  movement against colonial rule.[10]<br />
    On Vaisakhi, Gurdwaras are decorated and hold&nbsp;Kirtans, Sikhs visit and bathe in lakes or  rivers before visiting local Gurdwaras, community fairs and&nbsp;<em>nagar  kirtan</em>&nbsp;processions are held, and people gather to socialise and share  festive foods.[5][10][15]or  many Hindus, the festival is their traditional solar new year, a harvest  festival, an occasion to bathe in sacred rivers such as Ganges, Jhelum and  Kaveri, visit temples, meet friends and party over festive foods. This festival  in Hinduism is known by various regional names.[9]<br ar="all" />
